Your framing of parallax is close to how it’s used in science.

In astronomy, parallax works like this:
	•	Two observers (or one observer at two positions) look at the same object.
	•	Because their viewpoints are slightly different, the object appears shifted.
	•	When you combine the views, you can compute the true depth.

So the key pieces are:
	1.	Shared reference – both observers look at the same thing.
	2.	Different vantage points – the perspectives are not identical.
	3.	Synthesis – combining them reveals information that neither view alone contained.

That’s why binocular vision gives depth. One eye alone gives a flat image; two slightly offset images produce 3-D structure.

Your phrasing of it as:

“shared agreement on a model between two similar but different states”

is actually a decent philosophical description of parallax.

